    "Let me analyze this reaction to identify the roles of reagents, solvent, and catalyst.\n\nLooking at the reaction:\n- Reactants: CO (methanol), Cc1ccc(S(=O)(=O)C2=C[C@H]3OC(C)(C)O[C@H]3[C@@H](NC(=O)OC(C)(C)C)C2)cc1 (substrate with an acetonide protecting group), Cc1ccc(S(=O)(=O)O)cc1 (p-toluenesulfonic acid, TsOH)\n- Product: Cc1ccc(S(=O)(=O)C2=C[C@@H](O)[C@@H](O)[C@@H](NC(=O)OC(C)(C)C)C2)cc1 (diol product - acetonide removed)\n\nThe transformation is clearly an acetonide deprotection. The acetonide group (OC(C)(C)O) in the substrate is cleaved to give two hydroxyl groups (diol) in the product.\n\n- **TsOH (p-toluenesulfonic acid)**: This is the catalyst/acid that promotes the acetonide cleavage.\n- **MeOH (methanol)**: This is the solvent for the reaction.\n- The substrate with the acetonide group is the main reactant.\n\nSo the roles are:\n- CO (MeOH): Solvent\n- Cc1ccc(S(=O)(=O)O)cc1 (TsOH): Catalyst\n- Cc1ccc(S(=O)(=O)C2=C[C@H]3OC(C)(C)O[C@H]3[C@@H](NC(=O)OC(C)(C)C)C2)cc1: Reactant (substrate)\n\nLet me format this as a condition_role_mapping."
